With Phillips' contribution to the field economics and control theory became entwined in a new way. [...] captured this feeling when he wrote about the restoration of the machine by him and his collegue [engineering and economics were inseparable.] 

There is something strange about Philips' career, with a minimal publication record and not an outstanding academic background it seems strange that LSE should have employed him at all and that when they did that he should rise to the status of professor so quickly. [...] dismissed the idea that Phillips could have been a workaholic, [...].

